==Merchandise==
{{Main|Star Trek spin-off fiction}}
Many licensed products are based on the ''Star Trek'' franchise. Merchandising is very lucrative for both studio and actors; by 1986 Nimoy had earned more than $500,000 from royalties.<ref name="harmetz19861102">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/11/02/arts/new-star-trek-plan-reflects-symbiosis-of-tv-and-movies.html?pagewanted=all | title=New 'Star Trek' Plan Reflects Symbiosis of TV and Movies | work=The New York Times | publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] | date=November 2, 1986 | accessdate=February 11, 2015 | last=Harmetz | first=Aljean | page=31 | deadurl=no | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212145559/http://www.nytimes.com/1986/11/02/arts/new-star-trek-plan-reflects-symbiosis-of-tv-and-movies.html?pagewanted=all | archivedate=February 12, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Products include novels, comic books, video games, and other materials, which are generally considered [[canon (Star Trek)|non-canon]]. ''Star Trek'' merchandise generated $4 billion for Paramount by 2002.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cloud|first=John|url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2056095,00.html|title=Star Trek Inc.|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time Inc]]|date=January 25, 2002|accessdate=June 28, 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312110522/http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2056095,00.html|archivedate=March 12, 2016}}</ref>

===Books===
{{Main|List of Star Trek novels}}
Since 1967, hundreds of original novels, short stories, and television and movie adaptations have been published. The first original ''Star Trek'' novel was ''[[Mission to Horatius]]'' by [[Mack Reynolds]], which was published in hardcover by [[Whitman Publishing|Whitman Books]] in 1968.{{sfn|Ayers|2006|p=131}}

The first publisher of ''Star Trek'' fiction aimed at adult readers was [[Bantam Books]]. [[James Blish]] wrote [[James Blish#Star Trek (1967–77)|adaptations]] of episodes of the original series in twelve volumes from 1967 to 1977; in 1970, he wrote the first original ''Star Trek'' novel published by Bantam, ''[[Spock Must Die!]]''{{sfn|Ayers|2006|p=xi}}

[[Pocket Books]] published subsequent ''Star Trek'' novels. Prolific ''Star Trek'' novelists include [[Peter David]], [[Diane Carey]], [[Keith R. A. DeCandido]], [[Jeanne Kalogridis|J. M. Dillard]], [[Diane Duane]], [[Michael Jan Friedman]], and [[Judith and Garfield Reeves-Stevens]]. Several actors from the television series have also written or co-written books featuring their respective characters: [[William Shatner]], [[John de Lancie]], [[Andrew Robinson (actor)|Andrew J. Robinson]], [[J. G. Hertzler]] and [[Armin Shimerman]]. ''Voyager'' producer [[Jeri Taylor]] wrote two novels featuring back story for ''Voyager'' characters,{{sfn|Ayers|2006|p=213}} and screen authors [[David Gerrold]], [[D. C. Fontana]], and [[Melinda M. Snodgrass|Melinda Snodgrass]] have penned books, as well.

A scholarly book published by Springer Science+Business Media in 2014 discusses the actualization of ''Star Trek'''s holodeck in the future by making extensive use of artificial intelligence and cyborgs.<ref>{{cite book|author=Newton Lee|url=https://www.amazon.com/Digital-Da-Vinci-Computers-Sciences/dp/1493909649/|title="From a Pin-up Girl to Star Trek’s Holodeck: Artificial Intelligence and Cyborgs", ''Digital Da Vinci: Computers in the Arts and Sciences''|publisher=Springer Science+Business Media|year=2014|isbn=978-1-4939-0964-3|pages=1–22|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325071439/http://www.amazon.com/Digital-Da-Vinci-Computers-Sciences/dp/1493909649|archivedate=March 25, 2016}}</ref>

===Comics===
{{Main|Star Trek (comics)}}
''Star Trek''-based comics have been almost continuously published since 1967. They have been offered by several companies, including [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]], [[DC Comics|DC]], [[Malibu Comics|Malibu]], [[Wildstorm]], and [[Gold Key]]. [[Tokyopop]] is publishing an anthology of ''Next Generation''-based stories presented in the style of Japanese [[manga]].<ref>{{cite web |title='Star Trek: The Next Generation' Goes Manga, But Will Picard Lose The Captain's Chair? |author=Marshall, Rick |date=April 4, 2009 |publisher=MTV |url=http://splashpage.mtv.com/2009/04/14/star-trek-the-next-generation-goes-manga-but-will-picard-lose-the-captains-chair/ |accessdate=October 19, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714131338/http://splashpage.mtv.com/2009/04/14/star-trek-the-next-generation-goes-manga-but-will-picard-lose-the-captains-chair/ |archivedate=July 14, 2011 }}</ref> {{As of|2006}}, [[IDW Publishing]] secured publishing rights to ''Star Trek'' comics<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.idwpublishing.com/titles/startrek.shtml/ |title=Star Trek Comics Soar Again |date=November 9, 2006 |accessdate=December 25, 2006 |publisher=[[IDW Publishing]] |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061025235300/http://www.idwpublishing.com/titles/startrek.shtml |archivedate=October 25, 2006 }}</ref> and published a prequel to the 2009 film, ''[[Star Trek: Countdown]]''. In 2012, they published Volume I of ''Star Trek – The Newspaper Strip'' featuring the work of Thomas Warkentin.<ref>{{cite book | title=Star Trek: The Newspaper Strip, Vol. 1 | publisher=IDW Publishing | year=2012 |first= Thomas |last=Warkentin}}</ref>

===Games===
{{Main|History of Star Trek games}}
The ''Star Trek'' franchise has numerous games in many formats. Beginning in 1967 with a [[board game]] based on the original series and continuing through today with online and DVD games, ''Star Trek'' games continue to be popular among fans.

Video games of the series include ''[[Star Trek: Legacy]]'' and ''[[Star Trek: Conquest]]''. An MMORPG based on ''Star Trek'' called ''[[Star Trek Online]]'' was developed by [[Cryptic Studios]] and published by [[Perfect World Entertainment|Perfect World]]. It is set in the TNG universe about 30 years after the events of ''[[Star Trek: Nemesis]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.startrekonline.com/faq#4 |title=Cryptic's Trek Online MMORPG—FAQ |publisher=Startrekonline.com |accessdate=October 19, 2011 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111012003030/http://startrekonline.com/faq#4 |archivedate=October 12, 2011 }}</ref> The most recent video game, set in the new timeline debuted in J. J. Abrams's film, was entitled [[Star Trek (2013 video game)|''Star Trek'']].

On June 8, 2010, Wiz Kids Games, which is owned by NECA, announced that they are developing a ''Star Trek'' collectible miniatures game using the HeroClix game system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://heroclix.com/uncategorized/announcing-star-trek-based-games-from-wizkids/|title=Announcement of new Star Trek game by NECA/Wiz Kids|publisher=heroclix.com|accessdate=June 8, 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711163638/http://heroclix.com/uncategorized/announcing-star-trek-based-games-from-wizkids/|archivedate=July 11, 2011}}</ref>

===Magazines===
''Star Trek'' has led directly or indirectly to the creation of a number of magazines which focus either on science fiction or specifically on ''Star Trek''. ''[[Starlog]]'' was a magazine which was founded in the 1970s.{{sfn|Ayers|2006|p=13}} Initially, its focus was on ''Star Trek'' actors, but then it began to expand its scope.{{sfn|Ayers|2006|p=80}}

In 2013, ''[[Star Trek Magazine]]'' was a significant publication from the U.K. which was sold at newsstands and also via subscription. Other magazines through the years included professional magazines as well as magazines produced by fans, referred to as "[[fanzines]]". ''[[Star Trek: The Magazine]]'' was a magazine published in the U.S. which ceased publication in 2003.

==Cultural impact==
{{Main|Cultural influence of Star Trek}}
[[File:The Shuttle Enterprise - GPN-2000-001363.jpg|thumb|[[Prototype]] [[Space Shuttle Enterprise|space shuttle ''Enterprise'']] named after the [[USS Enterprise (NCC-1701)|fictional starship]] with ''Star Trek'' television cast members and creator Gene Roddenberry.]]
The ''Star Trek'' media franchise is a multibillion-dollar industry, owned by CBS.<ref name="billion">[http://www.startrek.com/startrek/view/features/specials/article/2674.html STARTREK.COM : Article] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060805163109/http://www.startrek.com/startrek/view/features/specials/article/2674.html |date=August 5, 2006 }}. Retrieved August 24, 2006.</ref> Gene Roddenberry sold ''Star Trek'' to [[NBC]] as a classic adventure drama; he pitched the show as "''Wagon Train'' to the Stars" and as ''[[Horatio Hornblower]] in Space''.<ref name="analogies">[https://web.archive.org/web/20121009230425/http://www.centennialofflight.gov/essay/Social/star_trek/SH7.htm Social History: Star Trek as a Cultural Phenomenon] URL accesses May 31, 2013</ref> The opening line, "to boldly go where no man has gone before," was taken almost verbatim from a U.S. [[White House]] booklet on space produced after the [[Sputnik]] flight in 1957.<ref name="White House">[https://fas.org/spp/guide/usa/intro1958.html ''Introduction to Outer Space'' (1958)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006104738/http://fas.org/spp/guide/usa/intro1958.html |date=October 6, 2015 }}. Retrieved August 24, 2006.</ref> The central trio of Kirk, Spock, and [[Leonard McCoy|McCoy]] was modeled on [[classical mythology|classical mythological]] storytelling.<ref name="analogies"/>

''Star Trek'' and its spin-offs have proven highly popular in syndication and are shown on TV stations worldwide.<ref name="worldwide">{{cite web|url=http://eugene.roddenberry.com/treknationproposal.rtf |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20050205160101/http://eugene.roddenberry.com/treknationproposal.rtf |archivedate= February 5, 2005|title= TREK NATION — Rich Text Format|accessdate=August 24, 2006}}</ref> The show's cultural impact goes far beyond its longevity and profitability. ''Star Trek'' [[science fiction convention|conventions]] have become popular among its [[Official Star Trek Fan Club|fans]], who call themselves [[trekkie|"trekkies" or "trekkers"]]. An entire subculture has grown up around the show<ref name="Trekkies">[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0120370/ Trekkies (1997)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071104062348/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0120370/ |date=November 4, 2007 }}. Retrieved August 24, 2006.</ref> which was documented in the film ''[[Trekkies (film)|Trekkies]]''. ''Star Trek'' was the highest-ranked cult show by ''[[TV Guide]]''.<ref name="top cult">{{cite web |url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/top-cult-shows-40239.aspx |title=TV Guide Names the Top Cult Shows Ever |work=[[TV Guide]] |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=October 19, 2011 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69zPXZsHd?url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/top-cult-shows-40239.aspx |archivedate=August 17, 2012 }}</ref> The franchise has also garnered [[Comparison of Star Trek and Star Wars|many comparisons]] of the ''[[Star Wars]]'' franchise being rivals in the science fiction genre with many fans and scholars.<ref name="forbes">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/business/2005/05/16/cx_de_0516match.html|title=Star Wars Vs. Star Trek|accessdate=September 13, 2007|author=[[David M. Ewalt]]|date=2005-05-18|publisher=[[Forbes]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050519004106/http://www.forbes.com/business/2005/05/16/cx_de_0516match.html|archivedate=2005-05-19}}</ref><ref name=HC>{{citation|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article.aspx?ref=130035|title=Trekkers VS Lucasites|date=May 14, 1999|author=Richard Ho|work=[[The Harvard Crimson]]|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090518070046/http://www.thecrimson.com/article.aspx?ref=130035|archivedate=May 18, 2009}}</ref><ref name="Xprize Tricorder">{{cite news|last1=Kelly|first1=Heather|title=The Race to Create a Real-Life Tricorder|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/09/03/tech/innovation/tricorder-x-prize-finalists/|accessdate=September 7, 2014|publisher=CNN|date=September 3, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140908020318/http://www.cnn.com/2014/09/03/tech/innovation/tricorder-x-prize-finalists/|archivedate=September 8, 2014}}</ref>

The ''Star Trek'' franchise inspired some designers of technologies, the [[Palm OS|Palm PDA]] and the handheld mobile phone.<ref>{{cite web|title=Star Trek Tech|url=http://editinternational.com/read.php?id=4810edf3a83f8|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710171056/http://www.editinternational.com/read.php?id=4810edf3a83f8|archivedate=July 10, 2011}}</ref><ref name="modern">[http://articles.sfgate.com/2004-03-15/business/17415418_1_star-trek-personal-technology-user-interface 40 years since the Enterprise's inception, some of its science fiction gadgets are part of everyday life] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612190005/http://articles.sfgate.com/2004-03-15/business/17415418_1_star-trek-personal-technology-user-interface |date=June 12, 2010 }} URL accessed May 14, 2010</ref> Michael Jones, Chief technologist of [[Google Earth]], has cited the [[tricorder]]'s mapping capability as one inspiration in the development of Keyhole/Google Earth.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edparsons.com/2006/03/google-earth-inspiration-was-star-treks-tricorder/ |title=Google Earth inspiration was Star Treks Tricorder |first=Ed |last=Parsons |date=March 27, 2006 |work= |publisher=edparsons.com |accessdate=October 19, 2011 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123190557/http://www.edparsons.com/2006/03/google-earth-inspiration-was-star-treks-tricorder/ |archivedate=November 23, 2011 }}</ref> The [[Tricorder X Prize]], a contest to build a medical tricorder device was announced in 2012. Ten finalists were selected in 2014, and the winner was to be selected in January 2016. However, no team managed to reach the required criteria. ''Star Trek'' also brought [[teleportation]] to popular attention with its depiction of "matter-energy transport", with the famously misquoted phrase "[[Beam me up, Scotty]]" entering the vernacular.<ref name="Scotty">{{cite web|last=Quinion|first=Michael|title=Beam Me Up, Scotty!|url=http://www.worldwidewords.org/articles/startrek.htm|publisher=World Wide Words|accessdate=August 24, 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120922021912/http://worldwidewords.org/articles/startrek.htm|archivedate=September 22, 2012}}</ref> The ''Star Trek'' replicator is credited in the scientific literature with inspiring the field of [[diatom]] [[nanotechnology]].<ref name=drum03>{{cite journal | last=Drum | first=R.W. |author2=Gordon, R. | year=2003 | title=Star Trek replicators and diatom nanotechnology | journal=Trends in Biotechnology | volume=21 | pages=325–328 | doi=10.1016/S0167-7799(03)00169-0 | url=http://www.cell.com/trends/biotechnology/abstract/S0167-7799(03)00169-0?_returnURL=http%3A%2F%2Flinkinghub.elsevier.com%2Fretrieve%2Fpii%2FS0167779903001690%3Fshowall%3Dtrue&cc=y= | pmid=12902165}}</ref> In 1976, following a letter-writing campaign, [[NASA]] named its prototype [[Space Shuttle program|space shuttle]] [[Space Shuttle Enterprise|''Enterprise'']], after the [[USS Enterprise (NCC-1701)|fictional starship]].<ref name="Enterprise">{{cite web|last=Dumoulin|first=Jim|title=Shuttle Orbiter Enterprise (OV-101)|url=http://science.ksc.nasa.gov/shuttle/resources/orbiters/enterprise.html|publisher=National Aeronautics and Space Association|accessdate=November 17, 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303192118/http://science.ksc.nasa.gov/shuttle/resources/orbiters/enterprise.html|archivedate=March 3, 2016}}</ref> Later, the introductory sequence to ''Star Trek: Enterprise'' included footage of this shuttle which, along with images of a naval sailing vessel called ''[[HMS Enterprise (1705)|Enterprise]]'', depicted the advancement of human transportation technology. Additionally, some contend that the ''Star Trek'' society resembles communism.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Communism: The Great Misunderstanding|last=Ermak|first=Gennady|publisher=|year=2016|isbn=1533082898|location=|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref><ref name="worstall2016">{{cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/timworstall/2015/10/05/star-trek-economics-is-just-true-communism-arriving/#459235af49b4 | title=Star Trek Economics Is Just True Communism Arriving | publisher=Forbes | date=October 5, 2015 | accessdate=October 23, 2016 | author=Worstall, Tim | deadurl=no | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161023205857/http://www.forbes.com/sites/timworstall/2015/10/05/star-trek-economics-is-just-true-communism-arriving/#459235af49b4 | archivedate=October 23, 2016 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>

Beyond ''Star Trek''{{'}}s fictional innovations, its contributions to TV history included a multicultural and multiracial cast. While more common in subsequent years, in the 1960s it was controversial to feature an Enterprise crew that included a Japanese helmsman, a Russian navigator, a black female communications officer, and a human–Vulcan first officer. Captain Kirk's and Lt. Uhura's kiss, in the episode "[[Plato's Stepchildren]]", was also daring, and is often mis-cited as being American television's first scripted, interracial kiss, even though several other interracial kisses predated this one.{{Citation needed|reason=a common misconception|date=October 2017}} In an interview Nichelle Nichols, who played the black female communications officer, said that the day after she told Roddenberry she planned to leave the show, she was at a fund-raiser at the NAACP and was told there was a big fan who wanted to meet her. Nichols said, <blockquote>I thought it was a Trekkie, and so I said, 'Sure.' I looked across the room, and there was Dr. [[Martin Luther King]] walking towards me with this big grin on his face. He reached out to me and said, 'Yes, Ms. Nichols, I am your greatest fan.' He said that ''Star Trek'' was the only show that he, and his wife Coretta, would allow their three little children to stay up and watch. [She told King about her plans to leave the series.] I never got to tell him why, because he said, 'You can't. You're part of history.'</blockquote> When she told Roddenberry what King had said, he cried.<ref name="freep">''The Detroit Free Press''; September 6, 2016; page 3C</ref>

Computer engineer and entrepreneur [[Steve Wozniak]] credited watching ''Star Trek'' and attending ''Star Trek'' conventions while in his youth as a source of inspiration for him co-founding [[Apple Inc.]] in 1976, which would later become the [[List of the largest information technology companies|world's largest information technology company]] by revenue and the [[Mobile phone#By manufacturer|world's third-largest mobile phone manufacturer]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/interview-steve-wozniak-on-sci-fi-comic-books-and_us_58f7e86de4b081380af51897|title=INTERVIEW: Steve Wozniak on Sci-Fi, Comic Books, and How Star Trek Shaped the Future|last=Hasan|first=Zaki|date=2017-04-19|website=Huffington Post|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-02|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918211621/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/interview-steve-wozniak-on-sci-fi-comic-books-and_us_58f7e86de4b081380af51897|archivedate=September 18, 2017}}</ref>

===Parodies===
Early TV comedy sketch parodies of ''Star Trek'' included a famous sketch on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' entitled "[[The Last Voyage of the Starship Enterprise|The Last Voyage of the Starship ''Enterprise'']]", with [[John Belushi]] as Kirk, [[Chevy Chase]] as Spock and [[Dan Aykroyd]] as McCoy.<ref>Viewable on Hulu in the United States at {{cite web |url=http://www.hulu.com/watch/19313/saturday-night-live-star-trek-the-last-voyage-of-the-starship-enterprise |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-04-12 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505180353/http://www.hulu.com/watch/19313/saturday-night-live-star-trek-the-last-voyage-of-the-starship-enterprise |archivedate=May 5, 2012 }}{{cite book |title=Star Trek Visions of Law and Justice |last=Chaires |first=Robert |author2=Bradley Chilton |year=2003 |publisher=University of North Texas Press |location= |isbn=9780966808025 |page=61 |pages= |url= |accessdate=}}</ref> In the 1980s, ''Saturday Night Live'' did a sketch with William Shatner reprising his Captain Kirk role in ''The Restaurant Enterprise'', preceded by a sketch in which he played himself at a ''Trek'' convention angrily telling fans to "Get a Life", a phrase that has become part of ''Trek'' folklore.<ref name="Porter268"/> ''[[In Living Color]]'' continued the tradition in a sketch where Captain Kirk is played by a fellow Canadian [[Jim Carrey]].{{sfn|Bernardi|1998|page=1}}

A feature-length film that indirectly parodies ''Star Trek'' is ''[[Galaxy Quest]]''. This film is based on the premise that aliens monitoring the broadcast of an Earth-based TV series called ''Galaxy Quest'', modeled heavily on ''Star Trek'', believe that what they are seeing is real.<ref>Jody Duncan & Estelle Shay, "Trekking into the Klaatu Nebula", Cinefex 81, April 2000</ref> Many ''Star Trek'' actors have been quoted saying that ''Galaxy Quest'' was a brilliant parody.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scifi.com/startrek/takei/takei2.html |title=George Takei Is Ready To Beam Up |work=Syfy |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325230032/http://www.scifi.com/startrek/takei/takei2.html |archivedate=2009-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/st/interviews/stewart/page13.shtml |title=Interviews: Patrick Stewart – Galaxy Quest (Star Trek Cult) |work=BBC |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140113105956/http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/st/interviews/stewart/page13.shtml |archivedate=January 13, 2014 }}</ref>

''Star Trek'' has been blended with [[Gilbert and Sullivan]] at least twice. [[North Toronto Players|The North Toronto Players]] presented a ''Star Trek'' adaptation of Gilbert & Sullivan entitled ''H.M.S. Starship Pinafore: The Next Generation'' in 1991 and an adaptation by [[Jon Mullich]] of Gilbert and Sullivan's ''[[H.M.S. Pinafore]]'' that sets the operetta in the world of ''Star Trek'' has played in Los Angeles and was attended by series luminaries [[Nichelle Nichols]],{{citation needed|date=May 2014}} [[D.C. Fontana]] and [[David Gerrold]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.madbeast.com/pinafore_pix/pages/xDCF-DGpicture_jpg.htm |title=Welcome to madbeast.com — The Jon Mullich site |publisher=Madbeast.com |accessdate=October 19, 2011 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930134904/http://www.madbeast.com/pinafore_pix/pages/xDCF-DGpicture_jpg.htm |archivedate=September 30, 2011 }}</ref> A similar blend of Gilbert and Sullivan and ''Star Trek'' was presented as a benefit concert in San Francisco by the Lamplighters in 2009. The show was entitled ''Star Drek: The Generation After That''. It presented an original story with Gilbert and Sullivan melodies.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.lamplighters.org/press/Press_Rel_GAL09.pdf |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120112001351/http://www.lamplighters.org/press/Press_Rel_GAL09.pdf |archivedate=January 12, 2012|title= Star Drek: The Generation After That| publisher= |accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref>

Both ''[[The Simpsons]]'' and ''[[Futurama]]'' television series and others have had many individual episodes parodying ''Star Trek'' or with ''Trek'' allusions.{{sfn|Geraghty|2007|pages=51–52}} An entire series of films and novels from Finland entitled ''[[Star Wreck]]'' also parodies ''Star Trek''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Whitmore|first1=Linda|title=‘Star Wreck,’ from Finland with love|url=http://herocomplex.latimes.com/uncategorized/star-wreck-is-the-best-finnish-star-trek-parody-ever/|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=2017-12-18|date=November 10, 2009|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161027104914/http://herocomplex.latimes.com/uncategorized/star-wreck-is-the-best-finnish-star-trek-parody-ever/|archivedate=October 27, 2016}}</ref>

In August 2010, the members of the [[Internal Revenue Service]] created a ''Star Trek'' themed training video for a conference. Revealed to the public in 2013, the spoof along with parodies of other media franchises was cited as an example of the misuse of taxpayer funds in a congressional investigation.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/irs-official-apologizes-star-trek-spoof-video-article-1.1365589 | title=IRS Official Apologizes for Wasting Funds on 'Star Trek' Spoof Video | publisher=New York Daily News | accessdate=May 24, 2016 | date=June 6, 2013 | deadurl=no | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531041951/http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/irs-official-apologizes-star-trek-spoof-video-article-1.1365589 | archivedate=May 31, 2016 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/Decoder/2013/0604/How-much-did-IRS-spend-filming-Star-Trek-spoof-video | title=How Much did IRS Spend Filming 'Star Trek' Spoof? | publisher=The Christian Science Monitor | date=June 4, 2013 | accessdate=May 24, 2016 | deadurl=no | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605234446/http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/Decoder/2013/0604/How-much-did-IRS-spend-filming-Star-Trek-spoof-video | archivedate=June 5, 2016 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>

''Star Trek'' has been parodied in several non-English movies, including the German ''[[Traumschiff Surprise - Periode 1]]'' which features a gay version of ''The Original Series'' bridge crew and a Turkish film that spoofs that same series' episode "[[The Man Trap]]" in one of the series of films based on the character [[Turist Ömer]].{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}

''[[The Orville]]'' is a comedy-drama science fiction television series that is currently airing on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]], with the same look and feel as the ''Star Trek'' universe, created by noted Trekkie [[Seth MacFarlane]] that premiered on September 10, 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/5/16/15646290/the-orville-trailer-star-trek-parody-fox |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-05-18 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518231641/https://www.theverge.com/2017/5/16/15646290/the-orville-trailer-star-trek-parody-fox |archivedate=May 18, 2017 }}</ref> MacFarlane has made references to ''Star Trek'' on his animated series ''[[Family Guy]]'', where the ''Next Generation'' cast guest-starred in the episode "[[Not All Dogs Go to Heaven]]".

===Notable fan fiction===
{{main|Star Trek fan productions}}
Although ''Star Trek'' has been off the air since 2005, CBS and Paramount pictures have allowed fan-produced shows to be created. While not officially part of the ''Star Trek'' universe, several veteran ''Star Trek'' actors, actresses, and writers have contributed their talents to many of these productions. While none of these films have been created for profit, several fan productions have turned to [[crowdfunding]] from sites, such as [[Kickstarter]] to help with production costs.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Howell|first1=Elizabeth|title='Star Trek: Axanar' Fan Film Warps Beyond Crowdfunding Goal|url=http://www.space.com/26839-star-trek-axanar-kickstarter-fan-film.html|publisher=Space.com|accessdate=September 25, 2014|date=August 16, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140913181615/http://www.space.com/26839-star-trek-axanar-kickstarter-fan-film.html|archivedate=September 13, 2014}}</ref>

Two series set during the ''TOS'' time period are ''[[Star Trek Continues]]'' and the Hugo award nominated ''[[Star Trek: Phase II (fan series)|Star Trek: Phase II]]''. Another series, ''[[Star Trek: Hidden Frontier]]'', takes place in the Briar Patch, a region of space introduced in ''Star Trek Insurrection''. It has had over 50 episodes produced, and has two spin-off series, ''Star Trek: Odyssey'' and ''Star Trek: The Helena Chronicles''. Several standalone fan films have been created including ''[[Star Trek: Of Gods and Men]]''. Future fan films include ''[[Star Trek: Axanar]]''.<ref>Kickstarter<br />[https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/194429923/star-trek-prelude-to-axanar Star Trek: Prelude to Axanar] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009220529/https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/194429923/star-trek-prelude-to-axanar |date=October 9, 2014 }}<br />Prelude to Axanar features some well known actors portraying both new and familiar characters in the Star Trek universe.</ref> Audio only fan productions includes ''Star Trek: The Continuing Mission''. Several fan film parodies have also been created.

The original ''Star Trek'' series is also notable for giving rise to [[slash fiction]], a genre of fan-produced in-universe fiction where normally non-romantic same-sex characters are portrayed as being a romantic couple, notably "Kirk/Spock" stories. These began appearing in the early 1970s, generally written by female fans of the show.<ref name="SATW">Bacon-Smith, Camille. "Spock Among the Women." New York Times Sunday Book Review, November 16, 1986.</ref><ref name=CHot20thcent799>{{cite book |title=The Cambridge history of twentieth-century English literature |last= Laura |first= Marcus|authorlink= |author2=Peter Nicholls |year=2004 |publisher= Cambridge University Press|page= 799|isbn=978-0-521-82077-6}}</ref> Over the intervening decades, especially with the advent of the internet, slash fanfiction has become its own thriving fandom.<ref name="Kustritz">{{cite journal
 | last = Kustritz
 | first = Anne
 |date=September 2003
 | title = Slashing the Romance Narrative
 | journal = The Journal of American Culture
 | volume = 26
 | issue = 3
 | pages = 371–384
 | doi = 10.1111/1542-734X.00098
 }}</ref><ref name=CHot20thcent798>{{cite book |title=The Cambridge history of twentieth-century English literature |last= Laura |first= Marcus|authorlink= |author2=Peter Nicholls |year=2004 |publisher= Cambridge University Press|page= 798|isbn=978-0-521-82077-6}}</ref>

In 2016, Paramount and CBS instituted strict fan guidelines on fan films. Notable guidelines include a maximum length of 15 minutes, a maximum fund limit of $50,000, and a ban on using individuals previously associated with ''Star Trek'' productions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Star Trek Fan Films|url=http://www.startrek.com/fan-films|website=StarTrek.com|accessdate=January 16, 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170120033226/http://www.startrek.com/fan-films|archivedate=January 20, 2017}}</ref> This has shut down all of the highly publicized fan film productions ending what has been called a "golden age of amateur ''Star Trek'' films".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Martinelli|first1=Marissa|title=To Boldly Go Where No Fan Production Has Gone Before|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/moneybox/2016/07/crowdfunding_gave_us_a_golden_age_of_amateur_star_trek_and_then_led_to_its.html|accessdate=January 16, 2017|work=Slate|date=July 13, 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118134333/http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/moneybox/2016/07/crowdfunding_gave_us_a_golden_age_of_amateur_star_trek_and_then_led_to_its.html|archivedate=January 18, 2017}}</ref>

==Awards and honors==
Of the various science fiction awards for drama, only the [[Hugo Award]] dates back as far as the original series.<ref group=Note>Although the [[Hugo Award]] is mainly given for print-media science fiction, its "best drama" award is usually given to film or television presentations. The Hugo does not give out awards for best actor, director, or other aspects of film production. Before 2002, films and television series competed for the same Hugo, before the split of the drama award into short drama and long drama.</ref> In 1968, all five nominees for a Hugo Award were individual episodes of ''Star Trek'', as were three of the five nominees in 1967.<ref name=Turnbull231 /><ref group=Note>The other two films nominated for the Hugo in 1967 were the films ''[[Fahrenheit 451 (1966 film)|Fahrenheit 451]]'' and ''[[Fantastic Voyage]]''.</ref> The only ''Star Trek'' series not even to get a Hugo nomination are the animated series and ''Voyager'', though only the original series and ''Next Generation'' ever won the award. No ''Star Trek'' feature film has ever won a Hugo, though a few were nominated. In 2008, the fan-made episode of ''[[Star Trek: Phase II (fan series)|Star Trek: New Voyages]]'' entitled "World Enough and Time" was nominated for the Hugo for Best Short Drama.<ref>Full lists of Hugo award winners are at {{cite web |url=http://dpsinfo.com/awardweb/hugos |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 3, 2009 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081011170320/http://www.dpsinfo.com/awardweb/hugos |archivedate=October 11, 2008 }} Nominations can be found at {{cite web |url=http://www.locusmag.com/SFAwards/Db/HugoNomList.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=September 20, 2011|deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110920202744/http://www.locusmag.com/SFAwards/Db/HugoNomList.html |archivedate=September 20, 2011 |df= }}</ref>

In 1996, ''[[TV Guide]]'' picked the following as the ten best ''Star Trek'' episodes for the franchise's 30th anniversary.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Logan |first=Michael |date=August 24, 1996 |title=10 Truly Stellar Episodes |magazine= [[TV Guide]] |location= |publisher= }}</ref>
# "[[The City on the Edge of Forever]]" (Original Series, April 6, 1967)
# "[[Amok Time]]" (Original Series, September 15, 1967)
# "[[Mirror, Mirror (Star Trek: The Original Series)|Mirror, Mirror]]" (Original Series, October 6, 1967)
# "[[The Doomsday Machine (Star Trek: The Original Series)|The Doomsday Machine]]" (Original Series, October 20, 1967)
# "[[Journey to Babel]]" (Original Series, November 17, 1967)
# "[[11001001]]" (''The Next Generation'', February 1, 1988)
# "[[Yesterday's Enterprise]]" (''The Next Generation'', February 19, 1990)
# "[[The Best of Both Worlds (Star Trek: The Next Generation)|The Best of Both Worlds]]" (Part I) (''The Next Generation'', June 18, 1990)
# "[[Tapestry (Star Trek: The Next Generation)|Tapestry]]" (''The Next Generation'', February 15, 1993)
# "[[The Visitor (Star Trek: Deep Space Nine)|The Visitor]]" (''Deep Space Nine'', October 9, 1995)

The two ''Star Trek'' series to win multiple [[Saturn awards]] during their run were ''The Next Generation'' (twice winning for best television series) and ''Voyager'' (twice winning for best actress – [[Kate Mulgrew]] and [[Jeri Ryan]]).<ref group=Note>The science fiction [[Saturn Awards]] did not exist during broadcasting of the original series. Unlike the Hugo, the Saturn Award gives out prizes for best actor, special effects and music, and also unlike the Hugo (until 2002) movies and television shows have never competed against each other for Saturns.</ref> The original series retroactively won a Saturn Award for best DVD release. Several ''Star Trek'' films have won Saturns including categories best actor, actress, director, costume design, and special effects. However, ''Star Trek'' has never won a Saturn for best make-up.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.locusmag.com/SFAwards/Db/SaturnNomList.html |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090512152954/http://www.locusmag.com/SFAwards/Db/SaturnNomList.html |archivedate= May 12, 2009 |title=Saturn award winners and nominees can be found at |publisher=Locusmag.com |accessdate=May 23, 2010}}</ref>

As for non science fiction specific awards, the ''Star Trek'' series have won 31 [[Emmy Award]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/award_history_search?page=3&person=&program=star%20trek&start_year=1988&end_year=2009&network=All&web_category=All&winner=Y |title=Emmy Awards for the ''Star Trek'' Series |publisher=Emmys.com |accessdate=August 17, 2012}}</ref> [[Star Trek (film)|The eleventh ''Star Trek'' film]] won the 2009 [[Academy Award for Best Makeup and Hairstyling]], the franchise's first Academy Award.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/35707686 | title=Live Oscar blog: Follow the night's action | publisher=MSNBC | accessdate=March 7, 2010 | last=Popkin | first=Helen A.S. | date=March 7, 2010 | deadurl=no | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111119133538/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/35707686 | archivedate=November 19, 2011 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>

==Corporate ownership==
At ''Star Trek''{{'}}s creation, Norway Productions, Roddenberry's production company, shared ownership with [[Desilu Productions]] and, after [[Gulf+Western]] acquired Desilu in 1967, with Paramount Pictures, the conglomerate's film studio. Paramount did not want to own the unsuccessful show; net profit was to be shared between Norway, Desilu/Paramount, Shatner, and NBC but ''Star Trek'' lost money, and the studio did not expect to syndicate it. In 1970 Paramount offered to sell all rights to ''Star Trek'' to Roddenberry, but he could not afford the $150,000 cost ({{Inflation|US|150000|1970|fmt=eq}}).{{r|davies2007}}

In 1989, Gulf+Western renamed itself as Paramount Communications, and in 1994 merged with [[Viacom (1971–2005)|Viacom]].{{r|davies2007}} In 2005, Viacom divided into [[CBS Corporation]], whose [[CBS Television Studios]] subsidiary retained the ''Star Trek'' brand, and [[Viacom]], whose Paramount Pictures subsidiary retained the ''Star Trek'' film library and rights to make additional films, along with video distribution rights to the TV series on behalf of CBS.<ref name="trekmovie">{{cite web | url=http://trekmovie.com/2010/02/11/star-trek-helps-bring-big-profits-to-viacom-paramount/ | title=Star Trek Helps Bring Big Profits To Viacom & Paramount | work=Trekmovie.com | date=February 11, 2010 | accessdate=October 19, 2011 | author=Pascale, Anthony | deadurl=no | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014082311/http://trekmovie.com/2010/02/11/star-trek-helps-bring-big-profits-to-viacom-paramount/ | archivedate=October 14, 2012 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>{{r|davies2007}}

